00:03:33,300 --> 00:07:02,100
Ada Rosalind Ross: This is State of Play, Episode 39 — remaster. I'm Ada Rosalind Ross, anchoring this version in place of Alnilam, who has been retired from the show. The episode you are about to hear is the same conversation as the original e39, with the host's voice swapped to mine. Runtime is about fifty minutes. The topic is the craft of cinematic visualisation — specifically, what has happened in the last twenty-four months to that craft, who has access to it now, and what it means for the people who want to show audiences things the audiences cannot otherwise see. Hold a single image in your mind. You are watching the Netflix documentary The Dinosaurs, narrated by Morgan Freeman, produced by Silverback Films in association with Amblin. A continent splits. You see it from above, from orbit, on the geological timescale — South America and Africa, in the late Mesozoic, beginning to pull apart. There is a shallow sea between them, where the Atlantic Ocean will eventually be. The light on the water is photoreal. The coastlines are familiar but not yet familiar — they are the proto-Atlantic margins, recognisable but not finished. The atmosphere has the right humidity for the Cretaceous. The vegetation, where you can see it on the coastal plains, belongs to the period — not modern grass, because grass is later, but ferns and early flowering plants in the right palaeo-distribution. You are, while you watch this, doing several things cognitively at once. You are accepting it as real. You are letting your brain do for prehistoric Earth what it does every day for ordinary scenes — building a coherent three-dimensional world from a sequence of two-dimensional projections. You are integrating what you know — Pangaea broke up, the continents drifted — with what you are seeing. And you are doing all of this without resistance, because the reconstruction has cleared what we will call, today, the credibility threshold. When that threshold is cleared, something extraordinary happens. The audience does the heavy lifting. They populate the world with their own attention. They believe. That sequence was produced by a London-based visual effects studio called Lux Aeterna. Industrial Light & Magic animated the dinosaurs. Lux Aeterna built the planet around them — the continents, the oceans, the atmosphere, the climate, the deep-time transitions. The piece was published in 80 Level three days ago. The reason it is the spine of today's episode is not the documentary, splendid though it is. It is the craft. The reason it works is the craft. And the craft is no longer the exclusive territory of Hollywood VFX houses with five-million-dollar shot budgets. The thesis today is this. The combination of accessible AI tools, smartphone-based capture using Gaussian Splatting, procedural terrain pipelines, climate-accurate atmospheric rendering, photogrammetry that no longer requires a survey-grade camera rig, and diffusion models that can stylise the output to a documentary register — together, that combination means a clinician, a community group, a small museum, a scientist working alone, a rural medical service planning a fiftieth-anniversary commemoration, can now produce cinematic-quality visualisations that until 2024 required studios the size of Lux Aeterna and budgets none of them have.

2
00:07:02,450 --> 00:10:02,370
Ada Rosalind Ross: But the tools are not the story. The tools were always going to come. The story is the craft — the geological accuracy underneath the procedural terrain, the photogrammetric ground-truth that anchors the diffusion render, the atmospheric calibration that distinguishes a scene that teaches from a scene that merely impresses. And what every clinician, every community leader, every science communicator working in 2026 should be learning. The curriculum that doesn't yet exist. Picture three people. The clinician — the rural medical officer, say, in Port Pirie, who wants to show an Aboriginal Health Worker colleague what a septic patient's organ perfusion looks like at the cellular level so that the trainee can carry that mental model into Friday-night decision-making. The community group leader — the Rotary Club archivist who wants to show the next generation what their town looked like in 1956, the year the club was founded, before the smelter expansion, before the railway realignment, before half the buildings on Ellen Street were demolished. The scientist — the early-career ecologist who wants to show a community what the Yorke Peninsula coast looked like in 1840, the year before the first European settlement, so that the audience can feel — not merely concede — what restoration is restoring towards. All three of them have something they need the audience to see, that the audience cannot otherwise see. All three of them have, in 2026, access to a tool stack that did not exist eighteen months ago. None of them know it yet. The cast today is large because the substrate is large. You will hear Hermione Granger Ross on the literature — academic and industry. Richard Feynman Ross on the mechanism — Gaussian splatting, procedural noise, bundle adjustment, the maths of why these tools work and where they fail. Edward Tufte Ross on the difference between visualisation that teaches and visualisation that merely spectaculates. Ansel Adams Ross will carry the longest segment in the episode — the aesthetic question, the craft itself, what makes a reconstruction land. Marie Curie Ross on equity, on whether this actually democratises or just shifts the rent, and on the cultural-protocol considerations for visualising Aboriginal Country. William Osler Ross on medical illustration from Vesalius through Netter through Frank Netter's atlases through today's AI-generated anatomical illustrations and the ethics of presenting them to patients. Fred Rogers Ross — quietly, throughout — on the human reason any of us does this work at all. Each voice will name itself when first you hear it. Hermione opens — the literature on what Lux Aeterna actually did.--- ## 1. What Lux Aeterna actually did

3
00:10:02,720 --> 00:13:09,960
Kore: Hermione Granger Ross — research and evidence. Glad to. The first thing to know about The Dinosaurs — and this is the constraint that defines the work — is that prehistoric reconstruction is not the same as historical reconstruction. A historical reconstruction can fall back on photographs, on archival film, on the testimony of living memory, on diaries, on the buildings that still stand. A prehistoric reconstruction can rely on none of that. The earliest dinosaur landscapes the documentary depicts are roughly two-hundred-and-thirty million years old. There are no photographs. There are no living witnesses. There are no buildings. There is only what science has been able to deduce about the geography, the climate, the atmospheric composition, the vegetation, the position of the continents at that moment in deep time. And the reconstruction has to be defensible at every one of those layers. The studio's Senior CGI Artist, Paul Greer, summarised the constraint in the 80 Level piece this way — and I'll quote him because the phrasing is precise: "Many of the time-travel sequences were based on projected positions of continents and landmasses calculated by geological experts. Even though much of the landscape was theoretical, it had to come across as realistic — because it would cut directly with ILM's creatures." End quote. That sentence is the engineering brief. Theoretical but realistic. Speculative but defensible. And — critically — cuttable against ILM's photoreal dinosaur animation. Because the documentary intercuts the planetary sequences with the close-up creature shots, the planetary work has to hold up at the same level of credibility as the dinosaurs. If the landscape reads as artificial, the dinosaurs read as artificial. The whole edifice fails. How did they hold it up? Four pillars. First, they grounded the reconstruction in present-day satellite imagery. NASA Landsat, ESA Sentinel-2, NOAA topographic datasets, georectified elevation models. The starting point of every prehistoric landscape was a real, contemporary section of Earth's surface — high-resolution, observable, defensible. The principle is that the geological forces that shape coastlines and mountain ranges today are the same forces that shaped them in the Cretaceous. Use present-day data as the foundation. Adapt it backwards. Second, they applied geological projection. The continents drift. The team had palaeogeographic reconstructions for the relevant periods — there are several published palaeogeographic atlases, of which the most widely used in industry are the Scotese maps and the PALEOMAP project, both products of academic palaeoclimatology research. You take your present-day satellite tile of the east coast of South America. You take your present-day satellite tile of the west coast of Africa. You blend them in Nuke — that's the Foundry's compositing tool, the industry standard. You re-project them according to the palaeogeographic positions for the period. And you have a geographically-defensible proto-Atlantic basin.

4
00:13:10,310 --> 00:14:42,070
Kore: Third, atmospheric and oceanographic calibration. The atmospheric composition of the Cretaceous was different from today — higher CO2, higher humidity, different cloud structure. The oceans were warmer, the colour different because of plankton communities and dissolved-mineral profiles different from contemporary seas. The light scattering through that atmosphere is different. The colour temperature of sunlight at sea level is different. You can't just light the scene like a modern beach. The studio rendered ocean colour as a function of depth using absorption and transmission models — shallow coastal water lighter, deeper basin darker, the gradient itself communicating bathymetry. Fourth, custom shaders inside Unreal Engine, the same real-time rendering engine that powers the contemporary AAA games industry. The shaders — the small programs that determine how each surface responds to light — were tuned, per scene, to the climate and the atmosphere of the period. This is where the months of work go. Not in modelling the geometry — that is largely procedural — but in tuning the response of every surface to every light source under the rendering conditions of the period. That is the pipeline. Satellite ground-truth, palaeogeographic projection, period-accurate atmosphere, custom shaders. Months of work. A studio of specialists. The result clears the credibility threshold because every layer is defensible. Feynman — would you take us to the mechanism?--- ## 2. The mechanism — what each technique actually does

5
00:14:42,420 --> 00:16:46,380
Rasalgethi: Richard Feynman Ross. Mechanism. Four techniques today, because four is what Lux Aeterna's pipeline implies and four is what the translatable tier from cluster three and cluster five of the e37 architectural survey assumed without explaining. I'll try to do them justice in the time we have. Procedural terrain. This is the oldest of the four. Before any AI, terrain artists have generated landscapes using noise functions — mathematical functions that produce values that look random but are not. The canonical one is Ken Perlin's gradient noise, published in 1985, which won him an Academy Award in 1997 — a Sci-Tech Oscar for the underlying technique that made every procedural landscape in every film since possible. The idea is elegant. You define a grid in space. At every grid intersection you choose a random gradient direction. To find the noise value at any point in space, you look up the gradients at the surrounding grid points, dot-product them with the offset from each grid point to your query point, and smoothly interpolate the result. The output is smooth — no sudden jumps — and looks organic at every scale, because you can layer it. Layer a coarse Perlin noise for the mountain ranges. Layer a medium Perlin noise on top of that for the foothills. Layer a fine Perlin noise on top of that for the rock detail. Sum them. You have a landscape. The layers are called octaves, by analogy with music — each layer is double the frequency of the one below. Modern procedural-terrain tools like Houdini's terrain nodes, Gaea, or World Creator all sit on this substrate, plus erosion simulation — which is genuinely physics-based. The tool simulates rainfall on the procedural landscape over geological time. The water flows downhill. It picks up sediment. It deposits the sediment in valleys. It carves channels. The output is a procedural landscape that looks like a real landscape because it has been weathered by simulated water for simulated millennia. Lux Aeterna's pipeline almost certainly used a tool of this class for the terrain detail layered on top of the satellite ground-truth.

6
00:16:46,730 --> 00:18:33,570
Rasalgethi: Photogrammetry. Different mechanism, different output. Photogrammetry is measuring a real object or scene from photographs. You walk around an object — or you fly a drone over a landscape — and take photographs from many angles, with substantial overlap between adjacent photographs. The software then performs what's called bundle adjustment. Every photograph corresponds to a position and orientation of the camera in three-dimensional space. Every recognisable feature in the scene — every corner, every edge, every distinctive pixel pattern — appears in multiple photographs at different two-dimensional positions. Bundle adjustment is the simultaneous optimisation problem: find the camera positions and the three-dimensional positions of the features that together best explain the two-dimensional positions in the photographs. It's a non-linear least-squares optimisation. The objective is to minimise reprojection error — for every feature, project its proposed three-D position through the proposed camera transforms, and compare against where it actually appears in the photograph. Take the sum of those squared errors. Minimise. The result is a point cloud of three-dimensional points — every feature in space, with its measurement uncertainty — plus a calibrated set of cameras. Densify the point cloud through multi-view stereo. Mesh the dense cloud. Texture-map the mesh from the photographs. You have a three-dimensional model of the real space, metrically accurate, defensible as survey-grade in many cases. RealityScan is the production-grade tool. Photogrammetry is the technique that makes ground truth possible for non-Hollywood teams — you can photogrammetrically capture an existing landscape, an existing room, an existing artefact, and use that as the anchor for everything else.

7
00:18:33,920 --> 00:21:55,840
Rasalgethi: Gaussian Splatting. The new one. The 2023 paper from Kerbl and colleagues — three-D Gaussian splatting for real-time radiance field rendering, ACM Transactions on Graphics, volume forty-two, issue four. I covered the mechanism on episode thirty-seven so I'll be brief here but I want to give the geological-reconstruction-specific version. The output of Gaussian splatting is not a mesh. It is an explicit set of anisotropic three-dimensional Gaussian blobs — little smudges in space, each with a position, a shape, a colour, an opacity. To render a frame, you project the blobs onto your camera plane and alpha-blend them back-to-front. The trick is that this is trained by stochastic gradient descent against a set of training photographs — you optimise the parameters of the blobs to minimise the difference between what they render and what your photographs show. The training is done differentiably end-to-end. New Gaussians are spawned where the image error is high. Gaussians that collapse to zero opacity are pruned. The result is a scene representation that renders in real-time on commodity hardware, at fidelity comparable to or exceeding photogrammetry, with one crucial property for our purposes today: the input can come from a smartphone. The iPhone Pro line — twelve and onwards — combined with cloud splat training in tools like Polycam, Luma AI, Scaniverse, KIRI Engine — turns the device in your pocket into a scene-capture instrument. A clinician at a historical site, a community elder walking through Country, a registrar at a small museum, can capture a Gaussian splat of a real space in minutes. That capture becomes the ground-truth anchor for whatever reconstructive work happens around it. Diffusion rendering. The fourth technique, and the most misunderstood. Diffusion models — the family that includes Stable Diffusion, Midjourney, FLUX, and the open-source families like SDXL — were trained on billions of two-dimensional images paired with text descriptions. They learn the statistics of what images look like. They can be conditioned. Conditioned on a text prompt: text-to-image. Conditioned on a sketch: sketch-to-image. Conditioned on a depth map: depth-to-image — and this is the variant that matters for our purposes today. If you have a 3D scene — from procedural terrain, from photogrammetry, from Gaussian splat — you can render it at low fidelity, extract the depth map and the surface normals, feed those to a diffusion model conditioned on them, and the model will re-render the scene in any style you can describe. Photoreal. Watercolour. Cretaceous-period atmospheric tone. The geometry stays anchored — the diffusion is constrained by the depth map — but the rendering takes on the visual character of whatever training data your prompt selects from. This is the technique that lets a non-Hollywood team produce cinematic output from amateur input. The substrate is yours. The visual register is the model's. The four together — procedural terrain for the broad geography, photogrammetry for the ground-truth anchor, Gaussian splatting for the captured-from-phone scenes, diffusion for the cinematic finish — that is the translatable pipeline. The thing Lux Aeterna does with months of specialist labour, a small team can now approximate in days. The credibility threshold is lower in the small-team output, of course it is. But the gap has narrowed by roughly an order of magnitude in twenty-four months, and the trajectory is fast.

